<Base title="About" lang="en" alt="/about" description="About Tiago Vaccari and Vaccari's Code Podcast.">
  <article>
    <h1>About</h1>
    <p>Hi, I'm <strong>Tiago Vaccari</strong>, host of Vaccari's Code.</p>
    <p>
      I've been writing software for over 20 years, and in that time I've learned that the most
      interesting part is never the technology itself — it's what you build with it. These days I
      lead AI initiatives and spend most of my time testing new ideas, breaking things, and figuring
      out how to put them back together, better.
    </p>
    <p>
      That same curiosity has carried me around the world. I was born in Jundiaí, in the countryside
      of São Paulo, Brazil; crossed the ocean to live in Bournemouth, on the English coast; and in
      2023 I started over from scratch in the United States, where I now live in Orlando, Florida.
      Every one of those moves reshaped how I think, work, and see the world. Away from the keyboard,
      I'm a father, a cyclist, and someone who just can't leave a good idea sitting on the page.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Vaccari's Code Podcast</strong> is exactly that itch to build made real: my living
      experiment in shaping a media presence with AI. It keeps up with what's happening in software
      development and Artificial Intelligence, digs out the stories that actually matter, and turns
      all of it into blog posts, newsletters, and narrated podcast episodes.
    </p>
    <p>
      But it's not automation on autopilot. Every piece of content goes through my own review before
      it goes live — that's what keeps the quality, the context, and a real point of view behind
      every word. The narration even uses a clone of my own voice, making the experience closer and
      more personal without giving up scale.
    </p>
    <p>
      On Vaccari's Code, I share this journey from the inside: software, AI, automation, tech
      careers, and the not-always-glamorous behind-the-scenes of building real digital products.
    </p>
    <p>
      Find me on <a href="https://github.com/tvaccari34" rel="me">GitHub</a>, or
      <a href="/en/subscribe">subscribe to the newsletter</a>.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
